  "response_text": "Here's a 3-day meal plan focused on heart-healthy foods. This plan emphasizes whole grains, fruits, vegetables, lean proteins, healthy fats, and low sodium. Always consult with a healthcare professional or a registered dietitian for personalized advice.\n\n### Day 1\n\n**Breakfast:**\n- Oatmeal topped with sliced bananas and a sprinkle of cinnamon\n- A handful of walnuts\n- A cup of green tea\n\n**Snack:**\n- A small apple with a tablespoon of almond butter\n\n**Lunch:**\n- Quinoa salad with chickpeas, diced cucumber, cherry tomatoes, red onion, parsley, and a lemon-olive oil dressing\n- A side of mixed greens with balsamic vinaigrette\n\n**Snack:**\n- Carrot sticks and hummus\n\n**Dinner:**\n- Grilled salmon seasoned with herbs and lemon\n- Steamed broccoli and brown rice\n- A side of mixed berries for dessert\n\n### Day 2\n\n**Breakfast:**\n- Greek yogurt topped with fresh berries and a tablespoon of flaxseeds\n- A slice of whole-grain toast with avocado\n\n**Snack:**\n- A pear\n\n**Lunch:**\n- Whole grain wrap filled with turkey breast, spinach, avocado, and sliced tomatoes\n- A side of baby carrots\n\n**Snack:**\n- A handful of unsalted almonds\n\n**Dinner:**\n- Stir-fried tofu with mixed vegetables (bell peppers, broccoli, and snap peas) in a low-sodium soy sauce\n- Served over brown rice or quinoa\n\n### Day 3\n\n**Breakfast:**\n- Smoothie made with spinach, banana, Greek yogurt, and a tablespoon of chia seeds\n- A slice of whole-grain toast with a thin spread of peanut butter\n\n**Snack:**\n- Celery sticks with hummus\n\n**Lunch:**\n- Lentil soup with a side salad (mixed greens, cucumbers, and tomatoes with lemon vinaigrette)\n- Whole-grain bread or crackers\n\n**Snack:**\n- A small handful of mixed nuts (unsalted)\n\n**Dinner:**\n- Baked chicken breast seasoned with herbs, served with roasted sweet potatoes and asparagus\n- A fruit salad for dessert (mixed fruits like melon, berries, and kiwi)\n\n### General Tips:\n- Stay hydrated by drinking plenty of water throughout the day.\n- Limit processed foods, added sugars, and saturated fats.\n- Choose healthy cooking methods like grilling, baking, steaming, or sautéing with minimal oil.\n- Adjust portion sizes based on individual needs and activity levels.\n\nFeel free to mix and match meals and snacks from different days to suit your preferences!",
